granted that a person was not fully human unless he or
she learned to master thoughts and feelings. In ancient
Sparta, in Republican Rome, and among the British upper
classes of the Victorian era, For example, people were
held responsible for keeping control of their emotions.
Anyone who lost his or her temper too easily was
deprived of the right to be accepted as a member of the
community. In other historical periods such as the one in
which we are now living, however, the ability to
control oneself is not always highly respected. People
who attempt it are often thought to be odd.

