#2008 9월 24번
Often the best form of communication with friends is,
surprisingly, silence. Friendship is not only about
what we say, but even more importantly about what we
do not. True friendship occurs when ‘information’ is
conveyed by absences of words. The point is to convey as
much as possible indirectly, ‘between the lines.’ The
reason such ‘negative’ communication is important is that
it requires a greater closeness than positive communication.
The greater the distance between sender and receiver, the
more the need for directness. Only when two or more
people share an enormous amount can the much more
economical negative communication take place.

